<!--
VOICING PLAN — Let Our Gladness Have No End (G major, 4/4):

This Czech carol has a characteristic stepwise-ascending melody (M1: G→A→B→C, M3: C→D→E)
interspersed with repeated-note phrases and inner-voice motion. The arrangement
mirrors these two textures: ascending phrases get flowing harmonic change each beat,
while repeated-note phrases get richer sustained voicings.

Phrase 1 (mm. 1–4): Opening ascent. Each beat gets a distinct chord to match the
melody's stepwise rise. I–V–I–IV on G→A→B→C, then V sustained through M4 to a
dotted half. LH "334" open voicings on each beat provide clean harmonic support.

Phrase 2 (mm. 5–8): Inner-voice phrase (D→D→C→C then B→B→A). IV→iii→IV→ii in M5
— a chain of falling thirds, each with a distinct LH root. The RH shadows the
melody at the 3rd throughout, creating a classical two-voice texture. M8 is a
deliberate G-arpeggio ascent (G→B→D) in the RH over a sustained LH I chord —
textural relief after the busy M5.

Secondary phrase (mm. 9–12): The piece builds in texture. M9 cycles V→vi→iii→IV
— the most harmonically active passage, with all four beats getting different
chords. LH tracks root motion below. M11 and M14 provide breathing points (half
note + rests) as structural punctuation.

Borrowed chord note (M12, "^Eb"): Eb is non-diatonic in G. The annotation sits on
pitch B4 (which belongs to Em/G chords). Substituted Em (vi) for beats 1+3, Am (ii)
for beats 2+4 — the Eb annotation likely indicates a coloristic diminished approach
that the diatonic chords approximate in context.

Final cadence (mm. 16–18): After the whole-rest M15, the final phrase opens with
G–C half-notes (I–IV) then descends D→Em→Am (V→vi→ii) in M17 before landing on
the G whole note (M18) with a 4-note I chord — the most sonorous moment.

VOICE LEADING HIGHLIGHTS:
- M1: RH upper voices descend B→A→B→C while LH roots follow I→V→I→IV — contrary
  motion throughout the opening measure.
- M5 (IV→iii→IV→ii): Bass steps down C→B→C→A in LH while RH maintains parallel 3rds
  above the melody. This is the most melodic inner-voice passage.
- M17: V→vi→ii (D→Em→Am) is the subdominant approach to the final I — avoids
  a plain V→I by substituting the vi as a deceptive resolution pass-through.

TEXTURE ARC:
- Opens (mm. 1–4): one chord per beat, lighter (3 LH notes). Active but clear.
- Middle (mm. 5–8): 4-note LH at crucial points (IV "333"), RH varies.
- Buildup (mm. 9–12): densest harmonic rhythm, 4-chord bars.
- Close (mm. 13–18): returns to half-note values, full 4-note LH on final chord.
